  "notes": "Test data generation approach:\n\n1. **Nominal cases (5 tests)**: Cover typical soil types (sand, loam, silt loam, clay), standard configurations, both root profile types (Zeng2001 and Jackson1996), both CLM physics versions (0 and 1), and varying organic matter levels (5-85 kg/m2).\n\n2. **Edge cases (4 tests)**: \n   - Shallow bedrock (nbedrock=3) to test bedrock property assignment\n   - Zero organic matter for pure mineral soils\n   - Maximum organic matter (130 kg/m2) at boundary\n   - Extreme clay content (60%) with very low hydraulic conductivity\n\n3. **Special case (1 test)**: Non-uniform depth discretization to test depth-dependent calculations\n\n**Physical realism ensured**:\n- All depths (z, zi) are monotonically increasing and >= 0\n- Clay and sand fractions sum to <= 1.0 (with implicit silt)\n- Organic matter in valid range [0, 130] kg/m2\n- Hydraulic conductivity > 0\n- Thermal properties > 0\n- Root parameters: roota_par, rootb_par > 0; rootprof_beta in [0, 1]\n- Watsat (porosity) in physically realistic range [0.339, 0.520]\n- Matric potential (smpsat) is negative (suction)\n- Clapp-Hornberger b parameter > 0\n\n**Dimension consistency**:\n- Each test maintains consistent array dimensions\n- npatch patches map to ncol columns via patch.column indices\n- ncol columns map to ntowers towers via tower_data.col_tower\n- PFT indices in patch.itype are valid for pftcon arrays\n- Texture indices in tower_data.tex are valid for soil_texture arrays\n- All soil layers use nlevgrnd=15, soil layers use nlevsoi=10\n\n**Coverage**:\n- Both root profile types (1=Zeng2001, 2=Jackson1996)\n- Both CLM physics versions (0=CLM4.5, 1=CLM5)\n- Range of soil textures from sand to clay\n- Organic matter from 0 to maximum (130 kg/m2)\n- Shallow to deep bedrock\n- Single and multiple patches/columns\n- Standard and non-standard depth discretizations"
